¥å±¥è¹’è·šï¼Œå› ä¸ºå‚ä¸çš„å’–å•¡é¦†å‘ç°é¡¾å®¢è½¬å‘ç»§ç»­æä¾›ä¸€æ¬¡æ€§æ¯å­çš„å’–å•¡é¦†ã€‚ â€œä¸€æ—¦ä½ ç»™æ¶ˆè´¹è€…é€‰æ‹©çš„é‚£ä¸€åˆ»ï¼Œä»–ä»¬å°±ä¼šäº«å—åˆ°ä¾¿åˆ©ã€‚â€&lt;/p>; &lt;figure data-media-id=&quot;1289898f99e6c26ba4f26c9f77acc56b740e0270&quot;>; &lt;img src=&quot;https://media.guim.co.uk/ 1289898f99e6c26ba4f26c9f77acc56b740e0270/0_151_2016_1210/1000.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;Louise Byrne, left, Ciara Treacy and Killian Treacy have led Killarney&#39;s scheme against single-use coffee cups.&quot; width=&quot;1000&quot; height=&quot;600&quot;>; &lt;figcaption>; &lt;span>;Louise Byrne, left, Ciara Treacy and Killian Treacy have led Killarney&#39;s scheme against single-use coffee cups.&lt;/span>; &lt;span>;Photograph: Rory Carroll/The Guardian&lt;/span>; &lt;/figcaption>; &lt;/figure>; &lt;p>;The campaign sought to enlist all of Killarney&#39;s 21 independent cafes, a lengthy process of individual face-to-face meetings, research, negotiations, a town hall-style gathering, a video, and more discussions.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;In addition to environmental benefits, the organisers said cafes could save money â€“ each disposable cup costs 20 to 30 cents â€“ and enhance Killarney&#39;s brand.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;Still, some cafe owners worried about forfeiting their stocks of single-use cups and alienating local customers as well as tourists. Eventually, nearly all signed up, and a credit union donated â‚¬5,000 for marketing, paving the way to the launch on 31 July. â€œIf it can be done in Killarney, at the height of the tourist season, it can be done anywhere,â€ said Killian Treacy, of Luna Deli + Wine.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;More than 50 local businesses are now on board, including a factory that told staff to bring only reusable cups to work.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;â€œIt&#39;s a great idea,â€ said Paul McClure, 43, visiting from San Diego. He had no objection to paying a â‚¬2 deposit for a takeaway cup that could be returned to any cafe in Killarney or 400 locations across Ireland, including Dublin airport, that are part of a wider campaign.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;Thorunn Einarsdottir, sipping a flat white, said the scheme could work in her native Iceland. â€œIt&#39;s really smart. It&#39;s like learning to organise your trash â€“ it&#39;s habit.â€&lt;/p>; &lt;figure data-media-id=&quot;3f55c0c1341006da0ae797301e1eff19642bcfbf&quot;>; &lt;img src=&quot;https://media.guim.co.uk/3f55c0c1341006da0ae797301e1eff19642bcfbf/0_38_2016_1210/1000.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;Thorunn Einarsdottir, who has moved to Killarney from Iceland, supports the elimination of single-use coffee cups.&quot; width=&quot;1000&quot; height=&quot;600&quot;>; &lt;figcaption>; &lt;span>;Thorunn Einarsdottir, who has moved to Killarney from Iceland, supports the elimination of single-use coffee cups.&lt;/span>; &lt;span>;Photograph: Rory Carroll/The Guardian&lt;/span>; &lt;/figcaption>; &lt;/figure>; &lt;p>;Replicating the scheme in cities would require government intervention because not every cafe would voluntarily sign up, said Killian Treacy. The Irish government&#39;s planned 20-cent tax on disposable coffee cups, known as the latte levy, is a start, but not enough, he said.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;Killarney cannot take success for granted â€“ businesses need regular reassurance and updates, said Ciara Treacy. â€œThere is a lot of hand-holding.â€&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;At least one holdout remains. â€œWe have a big stock of disposable cups to use up,â€ said Elaine Leahy of Noelle&#39;s cafe, which has stayed out of the scheme. That has had a knock-on effect on a neighbouring cafe, RÃ­-RÃ¡, which has resumed using single-use cups as well as reusables.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;Byrne is confident the scheme will continue to expand with help from community leaders and schools. â€œWe can&#39;t save the world but each of us can make a little change.â€&lt;/p>;&lt;br>;&lt;hr>;&lt;div>;è·å–æ›´å¤šRSSï¼š&lt;br>;&lt;a href=&quot;https://feedx.net&quot; style=&quot;color:orange&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;>;https://feedx.net&lt;/a>; &lt;